ard <i>g</i>, it is a variant of   Algar  .","Scottish and English: in Scotland, <i>Alger</i> may be a variant of   Algeo  .","German: from a shortened form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adalgar</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Aulgur","meanings":["English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Auger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Gaston, Lucien, Marcel, Mederic, Normand, Raoul, Cecile, Emile, Fernand, Gaetan.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Auger</i>, which can be from ancient Germanic <i>Adalgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gaira-</i> ‘lance, spear’, or <i>Albgari</i>, with the first element <i>alb</i> ‘elf’. Compare   Auge  ,   Oge  ,   Ogea  , and   Osier  .","English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Algar","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Algar</i>, representing the falling together of two Old English names, <i>Ælfgār</i> and <i>Æthelgār</i>, composed of the elements respectively <i>ælf</i> ‘elf’ or <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gār</i> ‘spear’. It could also be from the much rarer Old English personal name <i>Ealdgār</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘old’ + ‘spear’. In East Anglia, it is more probably a variant of   Alger   (Old Norse <i>Álfgeirr</i>). See also   Agar  ,   Elgar  ."]},{"name":"Alker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerhart.","South German: variant of   Alger  .","English: habitational name from Altcar, Lancashire. This name means ‘marshland by the River Alt’, from Old Norse <i>kjarr</i> ‘marsh’ and the river name <i>Alt</i>."]},{"name":"Ager","meanings":["English (mainly Essex, Suffolk, and Northamptonshire): variant of   Alger   or possibly of   Edgar  .","Danish: habitational name from any of several places called Ager, meaning ‘plowed land’ (from a cognate of the English word <i>acre</i>).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gari</i> (from <i>garwa</i>) ‘ready, eager’ or <i>gari</i> ‘spear’. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Alger was born in 1379, in Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Alger, was 46 and his mother, Joan of Lindsell, was 34. He married Annella de Rue in 1378, in Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 14 March 1418, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1379–14 March 1418":"1379–14. märts 1418","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1379–1418":"1379–1418","1380–1441":"1380–1441","1380–1404":"1380–1404","1400–1468":"1400–1468","1333–1412":"1333–1412","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","14 March 1418":"14. märts 1418","1 Jan 1412":"1. jaanuar 1412","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1468":"1468","1379":"1379","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1441":"1441","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lindsell,Essex,England":"Lindsell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1379–14 March 1418":"1379–14. maaliskuuta 1418","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1379–1418":"1379–1418","1380–1441":"1380–1441","1380–1404":"1380–1404","1400–1468":"1400–1468","1333–1412":"1333–1412","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","14 March 1418":"14. maaliskuuta 1418","1 Jan 1412":"1. tammikuuta 1412","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1468":"1468","1379":"1379","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1441":"1441","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lindsell,Ess